At every node, there are two different things we care about.

1. What can I return to my parent?

Parent can only continue through one side.

      10
     /
    5

If parent wants to use node 5, it can only take:

5

or

5 + left

or

5 + right

It cannot take both left and right because that would split the path.

So return value is:

node->val + max(leftGain, rightGain)


"What should a node return to its parent?"

The answer is:

node->val + max(leftGain, rightGain)

Then separately maintain a global answer for:

leftGain + node->val + rightGain

class Solution {
public:
    int ans = INT_MIN;

    int dfs(TreeNode* root) {

        if(root == NULL)
            return 0;

        int leftGain = max(0, dfs(root->left));
        int rightGain = max(0, dfs(root->right));

        ans = max(ans,
                  leftGain + rightGain + root->val);

        return root->val +
               max(leftGain, rightGain);
    }

    int maxPathSum(TreeNode* root) {

        dfs(root);

        return ans;
    }
};
